---
apply_to: ["crates/**/*.rs", "src/**/*.rs"]
---

## Implementation rules

### Mock-first workflow

Design changes start in the mock workspace. Types and trait
signatures land in `mock/crates/<name>/src/` first, validated by
`cargo check` in `mock/`, then by `cargo mock` (which also
regenerates `docs/`).

### Strategy markers are load-bearing

Every numeric type that has a precision/throughput tradeoff carries
`S: Strategy`. Default is `Warm`. The strategy drives storage
container width, operation semantics (wrapping vs saturating), and
SIMD lane count.

```rust
pub struct UFixed<const I: u8, const F: u8, S: Strategy = Warm> {
    bits: S::Container<I, F>,
}

pub type Ratio   = UFixed<0, 8, Warm>;
pub type Angle   = UFixed<9, 7, Warm>;
pub type Bool    = UFixed<1, 0, Hot>;   // explicit override
```

Strategies (summary — see
`design_rounds/202603241200_topic.arvo-strategy-markers.md` for the
full table):

| Strategy | Container | Arithmetic | Use case |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Hot` | minimum byte-aligned | wrapping | inner loops, known-safe range |
| `Warm` (default) | 2x logical, byte-aligned | wrapping (safe on single ops) | default |
| `Cold` | bitpacked minimum | widen-op-narrow | storage density |
| `Precise` | 2x logical, bitpacked | saturating | correctness-critical |

If you add a new numeric type and the type admits a precision
tradeoff, it MUST carry `S: Strategy` or justify the omission in
a code comment. The `strategy-marker-required` lint warns when a
new `pub struct`/`pub type` in a numeric crate lacks the parameter.

### Monomorphisation is the dispatch

- No `dyn Trait` anywhere.
- No `TypeId`, no `std::any::*`.
- Sub-crates are generic over trait bounds
  (`BitSequence`, `BitAccess`, `BitLogic`, `TotalOrd`, `Add`, `Sqrt`,
  `Recip`, `FromConstant`).
- Consumers pick concrete instantiations at the use site. The
  monomorphised function IS the type identity.

### Contracts before concretes

- `arvo` declares numeric primitives, strategy markers, and
  composable numeric traits.
- `arvo-bits` declares bit-level contracts (`BitWidth`, `BitAccess`,
  `BitSequence`, `BitLogic`) + opaque-bit concretes via allowlist
  (today: `Bits<N>`). **Arithmetic fielded structs live in L0 arvo;
  mask-specific concretes live in L2 arvo-bitmask.** A new arithmetic
  `pub struct` with fields in `arvo-bits/src/**` is a layering
  violation.
- `arvo-bitmask` picks `Mask64`, `Mask256`, `BitMatrix` concretes on
  top of `arvo-bits` contracts.
- `arvo-graph` / `arvo-sparse` / `arvo-comb` / `arvo-spectral` are
  generic over numeric trait bounds. They do not import `UFixed` or
  `IFixed` directly.

### Sizes are const

Every size lives at type level: `Mask64`, `Mask256`, `Seq<T, N>`,
`[W; N]`. No runtime resize. No runtime grow. If you reach for
`.push(`, `.resize(`, `.extend(`, `Vec::with_capacity`, you are
solving the wrong problem — either make the size const-generic or
the consumer owns the buffer.

### Zero platform dep

arvo does not call into the OS. No `std::thread`, `std::time`,
`std::fs`, `std::net`, no syscalls, no clocks. Everything is pure
compute on const-sized containers. Platform concerns belong in
consumer crates (notably `hilavitkutin`).

### no_std boilerplate

Every crate root (`src/lib.rs`) starts with:

```rust
#![no_std]
#![forbid(unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn)]
```

`#![forbid(unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn)]` makes unsafe blocks explicit
inside unsafe fns. `unsafe` itself is permitted where strictly
required for hardware intrinsics (e.g. `cttz`, `popcnt`) but must be
minimal and documented.

### Code conventions

- Target &lt; 300 LOC per file. Hard cap 500 (the `file-size` lint
  enforces this).
- Tests live alongside source in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`.
- No `panic!` / `unwrap` / `expect` in library code. Return
  `Option` / `Result`, or saturate (in `Precise`) / wrap (in `Warm`).
- Commit format: `type: lowercase imperative message`.
  See `skills/commit-style/SKILL.md`.
